## SECTION 1: FREAK SYNTAX — COMPLETE REFERENCE

### 1.1 Variables

```
pilot x = 42
pilot name = "Takeru"
pilot active = true
pilot ratio = 3.14
pilot x: int = 42          -- with explicit type
pilot x: word = "hello"
```

- Keyword: `pilot` (replaces `let` from other languages)
- Type annotation is optional — inferred from value
- No semicolons required (optional)
- Mutable by default

### 1.2 Functions

```
task add(a: num, b: num) -> num {
    give back a + b
}

task greet(name: word) -> void {
    say "Hello, {name}!"
}

-- Single expression shorthand
task square(x: num) => x * x

-- done keyword is valid alternate block closer
task cube(x: num) -> num
    give back x * x * x
done
```

- Keyword: `task`
- Return keyword: `give back`
- Print keyword: `say` (always available, no import needed)
- String interpolation with `{variable}` inside double quotes
- Blocks close with `}` OR `done` — both valid, both compile identically
- Arrow form `=>` for single-expression functions

### 1.3 Types — Primitive

| FREAK type | C equivalent       | Notes                                      |
|------------|--------------------|--------------------------------------------|
| num        | double             | Default numeric, context-narrows           |
| int        | int64_t            | Explicit signed 64-bit integer             |
| uint       | uint64_t           | Unsigned 64-bit                            |
| tiny       | uint8_t            | Single byte                                |
| float      | double             | Explicit float (same as num in Lite)       |
| float32    | float              | 32-bit float                               |
| big        | (not in Lite v1)   | Arbitrary precision — skip for now         |
| word       | freak_word*        | UTF-8 string (fat pointer, see runtime)    |
| bool       | bool               | true/false/yes/no/hai/iie all valid        |
| char       | uint32_t           | Unicode codepoint                          |
| void       | void               | Nothing                                    |
| [T; N]     | T arr[N]           | Fixed-size array                           |
| (A, B)     | freak_tuple_AB*    | Tuple (generate struct per unique combo)   |
| *T         | T*                 | Raw pointer (trust-me blocks only)         |

### 1.4 Types — Compound

```
-- maybe<T>: optional value
maybe<int>    -- has value or doesn't
some(42)      -- construct with value
nobody        -- construct without value

-- result<T, E>: success or error
result<int, word>
ok(42)        -- success
err("oops")   -- failure

-- List<T>: dynamic array
List<int>
[1, 2, 3]     -- literal

-- Map<K, V>: hash map
Map<word, int>
{ "a": 1, "b": 2 }   -- literal

-- Tuple
(int, word)
(42, "hello")  -- literal
```

### 1.5 Shapes (Structs)

```
shape Point {
    x: num
    y: num
}

-- Instantiate
pilot p = Point { x: 3.0, y: 4.0 }

-- Access
say p.x

-- With methods
shape Circle {
    center: Point
    radius: num
}

impl Circle {
    task area(self) -> num {
        give back 3.14159 * self.radius * self.radius
    }
}

pilot c = Circle { center: Point { x: 0.0, y: 0.0 }, radius: 5.0 }
say c.area()
```

### 1.6 Doctrines (Traits)

```
doctrine Displayable {
    task display(self) -> word
}

impl Displayable for Point {
    task display(self) -> word {
        give back "({self.x}, {self.y})"
    }
}

-- Generic with doctrine bound
task print_it<T: Displayable>(val: T) {
    say val.display()
}
```

### 1.7 Control Flow

```
-- if/else
if x > 10 {
    say "big"
} else if x > 5 {
    say "medium"
} else {
    say "small"
}

-- done form also valid
if x > 10
    say "big"
done

-- when (pattern match)
when x {
    1    -> say "one"
    2    -> say "two"
    _    -> say "other"
}

-- when with blocks
when status {
    "active"   -> { log(status); deploy() }
    "inactive" -> decommission()
    _          -> say "unknown"
}

-- for each
for each item in my_list {
    say item
}

-- for each with index (via enumerate)
for each (i, item) in my_list.enumerate() {
    say "{i}: {item}"
}

-- repeat
repeat 5 times {
    say "FREAK!"
}

-- while equivalent
repeat until condition {
    do_thing()
}

-- training arc (special loop)
training arc until power >= 9000 max 100 sessions {
    practice()
    receive_trauma()
}
-- compiles to: while loop with iteration counter cap
```

### 1.8 Destructuring

```
-- Destructure shape
pilot { x, y } = point

-- Destructure tuple
pilot (a, b) = my_tuple

-- Ignore fields
pilot { name, _ } = person

-- In for each
for each { key, value } in my_map.pairs() {
    say "{key}: {value}"
}
```

### 1.9 Closures and Lambdas

```
-- Arrow lambda (single expression)
pilot double = |x: num| => x * 2

-- Block lambda
pilot clamp = |x: num, lo: num, hi: num| {
    if x < lo { give back lo }
    if x > hi { give back hi }
    give back x
}

-- Type inference (types inferred from usage)
pilot is_positive = |x| => x > 0

-- Capture modes
pilot threshold = 100

-- Default: borrow (immutable reference to outer vars)
pilot check = |x| => x > threshold

-- Copy capture: copies value into closure
pilot check2 = copy |x| => x > threshold

-- Move capture: closure takes ownership
pilot handler = move |x| { process(x) }

-- Mutable capture
pilot count = 0
pilot counter = mut |_| { count += 1 }
```

### 1.10 Pipe Operator

```
-- |> pipes result of left into first arg of right
pilot result = data
    |> filter(|x| => x > 0)
    |> map(|x| => x * 2)
    |> take(10)
    |> collect()

-- Equivalent to:
pilot result = collect(take(map(filter(data, |x| => x > 0), |x| => x * 2), 10))
```

### 1.11 Error Handling

```
-- ? operator: propagate error upward
task parse_and_double(s: word) -> result<int, word> {
    pilot n = parse_int(s)?    -- if err, returns err immediately
    give back ok(n * 2)
}

-- check result
check result parse_int("42") {
    ok(n)    -> say "Got: {n}"
    err(msg) -> say "Error: {msg}"
}

-- or else: provide default on error/nobody
pilot n = parse_int(input) or else 0
pilot val = maybe_value or else "default"

-- check (unwrap maybe)
check find_user(id) {
    got u    -> say u.name
    nobody   -> say "not found"
}
```

### 1.12 Generics

```
task first<T>(list: List<T>) -> maybe<T> {
    if list.empty() { give back nobody }
    give back some(list[0])
}

-- Multi-bound
task log_sorted<T: Comparable + Displayable>(items: List<T>) {
    items |> sort() |> each(|x| => say x.display())
}

-- Generic shape
shape Pair<A, B> {
    first: A
    second: B
}
```

### 1.13 Borrowing

```
-- Immutable borrow
task print_name(lend p: Person) {
    say p.name
}

-- Mutable borrow
task rename(lend mut p: Person, new_name: word) {
    p.name = new_name
}

-- In FREAK Lite: borrowing is trust-based (no borrow checker)
-- The keywords are present and parsed but not enforced
-- Document this limitation clearly
```

### 1.14 Modules and Imports

```
-- Import from local module (file)
use tactics::{engage, Formation}

-- Import everything from module
use tactics::*

-- Import from Hangar dependency
use muvluv::{TSF, Eishi}

-- Aliased import
use cosmo::OrbitalStrike as Strike

-- Making things public (exported from a module)
launch task my_function() { ... }
launch shape MyType { ... }
```

### 1.15 Memory and Trust

```
-- trust me: unsafe block
trust me "reason" on my honor as .cadet {
    pilot raw: *int = alloc(100)
    raw.write(0, 42)
    free(raw)
}

-- Honor levels: .cadet .pilot .ace .commander .humanity
-- In FREAK Lite: trust me compiles to a plain C block
-- The message string and honor level are ignored at runtime
-- but logged at compile time

-- direct_order: inline assembly (skip in FREAK Lite v1)
```

### 1.16 Anime Keywords (FREAK Lite subset)

```
-- @protagonist: annotation, compile to comment in C
@protagonist
pilot takeru: Eishi = Eishi::new("Takeru")

-- @nakige: requires acknowledgement to call
@nakige
task sacrifice(pilot: Pilot) -> void { ... }

-- Call requires:
knowing this will hurt, sacrifice(ally)
-- or short form:
sadly sacrifice(ally)

-- @side_character: death flag monitoring
-- In FREAK Lite: emit warnings, not errors
@side_character
pilot hayase = Eishi::new("Hayase")

-- training arc: compiles to while loop with counter
training arc until x >= 100 max 50 sessions {
    x += 1
}
-- becomes:
-- int __arc_count = 0;
-- while (x < 100 && __arc_count < 50) { x += 1; __arc_count++; }

-- route: tagged union return type
-- In FREAK Lite: compile to int enum + value union
task confess(courage: num) -> route {
    if courage >= 100 { route TrueRoute }
    else { route BadEnd }
}

-- foreshadow: tracked variable
foreshadow pilot clue = get_clue()
payoff clue    -- marks it resolved

-- Operators (compile to C expressions):
-- PLUS ULTRA x  =>  x * (1 + emotion_intensity * emotion_intensity)
--                   (In Lite: x * 2.0, stub)
-- a NAKAMA b    =>  a + b + (a * b * 0.1)  (synergy bonus)
-- FINAL FORM x  =>  x * x  (with sleep(5) drama pause at compile time only)
-- x TSUNDERE    =>  !(x)  for bool, or -x for num
```

